[{"id":"VR860297","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Is the student’s claim correct? Why or why not?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR860297_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A resistor of resistance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"R\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>R</mi></math></span></span>, a battery of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"e m f\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"e m f\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>emf</mi></math></span></span> <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"open E\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"open E\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>Ɛ</mi></math></span></span>, and an ideal ammeter are connected in series. A <span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">nonideal</span> voltmeter is connected in parallel with the resistor, as shown. A student claims that the ammeter will measure current equal to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the fraction open E over R\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"the fraction open E over R\" overflow=\"scroll\"> <mfrac> <mi>Ɛ</mi> <mi>R</mi> </mfrac> </math></span></span>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a rectangular circuit diagram with a battery, a resistor, an ammeter, and a voltmeter. The circuit has two horizontal branches and three vertical branches. The battery is on the left vertical branch. The resistor is on the middle vertical branch. The ammeter is on the bottom horizontal branch to the left of the middle vertical branch. The voltmeter is on the right vertical branch.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR860297.g01.svg\" /></div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Yes, because the potential difference across the resistor is equal to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"open E\"><math alttext=\"open E\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>Ɛ</mi></math></span></span> even if the voltmeter is nonideal</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Yes, because the ammeter will measure the current in the battery</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">No, because the nonideal voltmeter will cause the potential difference across the resistor to change</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">No, because the finite resistance of the nonideal voltmeter will change the equivalent resistance of the circuit</p>"],"answer":3}]